:: docs/constalloc.txt
--[[pod_format="raw",created="2026-03-12 22:06:57",modified="2026-03-12 22:10:42",revision=6]]
Considering this model:

```
/// A highly unsafe category which provides raw blocks of memory sufficient for allocating a type.
///
/// Memory operated on by allocators does not handle initialization or deinitialization.
pub unsafe category Allocator<exception: Exception> {
    /// Perform a new memory allocation.
    unsafe fun allocate<T>(&self, count: USize = 1) throws Exception -> Pointer<to: T>
    
    /// Free a memory allocation.
    unsafe fun deallocate<T>(&self, _ pointer: Pointer<to: T>, count: USize = 1)
    
    /// Resize an existing memory allocation preserving the bit-pattern of overlapping data.
    unsafe fun reallocate<T>(&self, _ pointer: Pointer<to: T>, old_count: USize, new_count: USize) throws Exception -> Pointer<to: T> {
        let new: Pointer<to: T> = unsafe try self.allocate(count: new_count)
        for index in 0..<old_count do unsafe raw_copy(from: unsafe pointer[index], to: unsafe new[index])
        unsafe self.deallocate(pointer, count: old_count)
        new
    }
}
```

However, all of these would have const overloads
in an extension.

The language does not define a stack,
linear memory nor pointer arithmetic
(except in unportable conditional extensions
guarded to only work on platforms where that is
possible). Lifetimes are also strict.

The constant allocator would put the final constant
state of the allocation as constant data in the
output program (be it wasm, jvm, native, or
basically anything) and before the first
potential runtime access it would transparently
bitwise initialize the container with a runtime
allocation initialized bitwise with the expected
state, making it feel like it just worked.

This would inherently also work as an optimization
pass, since eager const evaluation would fold
any needlessly runtime code into a preallocation,
without a need for advanced machinery like LLVM.

Also, while constant evaluation is eager and implicit,
there are `const` functions which can only run at
compile time and can upcast normally runtime
values back to compile time because why not,
such as this:

```
const fun foo() -> Array<of: Int, count: 10> {
    let mut list = List<of: Int>()
    for i in 1...10 do list.append(i)
    .init(list) // const conversion initializer
}
```

:: docs/constarg.txt
--[[pod_format="raw",created="2026-03-25 22:02:12",modified="2026-03-25 23:14:32",revision=21]]
There are cases where compile time and runtime
worlds can exist separated in signatures.
`Parameters`, the generic compile time list,
and `arguments`, the dynamic values which can be
either runtime or compile time but either way
do not monomorphize the function.

This distinction is not always that clean.
Consider this fundamental function:

```
fun format<Argument...>(
    _ format: &String,
    _ args: &Argument...
) where (Argument: Formattable, ...) -> String
```

Should the format string be compile time or runtime?

Well, ideally we would like to format at runtime or
at compile time based on the input. If the string
is available at compile time we could save a lot of
time by pre-computing the format string parsing!
We can't make it a parameter however, because we
will forbid runtime-known format strings, and those
could be very useful for example when the format
strings are localized.

How can this be achieved then?

Inlining is one choice. If the function is inlined
it is possible to optimize the const knowledge away
because there is no ABI to uphold.

Another is const arguments:

```
fun format<Argument...>(
    _ format: const &String,
    _ args: &Argument...
) where (Argument: Formattable, ...) -> String
```

This specifies a monomorphization point.
If const known the compiler can choose
to monomorphize on the argument, something normally
not possible. Unlike relying on inlining this
approach allows reusing the implementation across
uses with identical const arguments. Unlike
parameters this can still be a runtime known value.

This is not a language feature at the moment,
but rather a consideration.

There is a second issue here, namely forced
monomorphisation on arguments. Would it be possible
to somehow bridge this, without runtime types?
I think it might be possible to do through a
new kind of constraint.

```
fun format(
    _ format: &String,
    _ args: &Argument...
) where Argument: Formattable.format -> String
```

Using a category with a (non parameterized)
homogeneous variadic list is normally not possible,
but what if what we actually care about is a single
function? This would change the calling convention,
making the *caller* perform the call, so the
variadic list is actually of `format` return type.
Notably, custom format strings would not work here
as those would depend on const parsing...
How would one even declare such dependency?

This is very clearly too much implementation detail
(any at all is too much) bleeding into language design.
It is however a good idea for the compiler to
decide to apply some messed up calling conventions
under the hood to do this. The ideal way to lower
a generic format function should be a single instance,
not inlining large amounts of code repeatedly, but
the burden should not be placed on the programmer.
It is also a waste for backends where generics
do not need to be monomorphized.

The current approach will be to not specify anything
around this feature. Time will tell what the correct
decision is here. Ideally the compiler can provide
a good balance on its own.

The optimization plan is:
- Analyze a variadic generic function.
- Does it always rely on a particular transformation?
- If so then delegate the calls to the caller.
- Do not monomorphize on those parameters.
- Profit (smaller, faster binaries)

Basically, pure category usage can be fast.
This has tradeoffs too however. Ugh.

:: docs/lowering.txt
--[[pod_format="raw",created="2026-03-09 21:30:40",modified="2026-03-09 21:55:52",revision=11]]
This is a document on how Strawberry language
constructs are lowered to Lua code.

Strawberry is a language specified very abstractly,
with optional unportable extensions such as pointers
meant primarily for interoperability. This allows
Strawberry to scale to arbitrary backends.

When bridging Lua and Strawberry code it might be
necessary to understand how the language is lowered,
especially more exotic concepts.

-----------------------------------------------------
Ownership and references

Since Lua is a managed language oriented around
reference types, ownership and references are
purely a safety, correctness and RAII feature handled
at compile time. There are exceptions to this:

- Lua value types, like numbers or booleans, are
wrapped in tables if on any code path they are
referenced mutably.

- Strawberry value types, so any copyable type,
almost always have no way of being represented
in Lua. On the other hand, aggressively copying
tables is not a very efficient way to go about this.
For this reason value types rely on a small Lua
runtime and a copy-on-write system.

Thanks to ownership tracking Strawberry can
handle deinitializers at compile time, inserting them
when appropriate for the destructive move system.

-----------------------------------------------------
Tuples

Since tuples are structural groups of values they
are mapped to individual Lua values, taking advantage
of multiple return value support. This is especially
relevant because a lot of language features use
tuples under the hood.

-----------------------------------------------------
Functions


:: docs/patterns.txt
--[[pod_format="raw",created="2026-03-11 08:45:38",modified="2026-03-11 09:31:22",revision=9]]
A note on pattern matching and adjacent features.

The language uses a few different categories of
patterns to encode correct semantics in the parsing
stage itself, with no need to resolve constants like
Rust and the ability to use runtime values in
patterns.

The basic form is unconditional destructuring,
something Rust syntactically confuses with pattern
matching causing ambiguous syntax like "let else".
Strawberry follows Swift instead.

let (a, (b, c)) = (1, (2, 3))
for (i, element) in sequence.enumerated() {}

let (mut a, b) = foo()
for (i, mut &element) in sequence.enumerated() {
    element += i
}

The let is extracted in front and elided entirely
in loop syntax, since unlike full patterns there
is no ambiguity as to what is binding or expression.

There exists a special statement parsed unambiguously
by virtue of top level parenthesized expressions not
being allowed, multiple assignment syntax, which
matches destructuring binding just assigning to
existing bindings instead.

(self.x, self.y) = self.position()

This is the destructuring pattern category.
The next one is full pattern matching and has
different syntax to distinguish its unique semantics.

when .Some(let v) = optional where v == 2 {
    print(v)
}

It even works as an expression.

let r = when .Some(let v) = optional {
    2 + v
} else {
    2
}

The keyword is different from "if" expressions to
avoid parsing ambiguity, but I chose not to opt for
"if match" as that would be too verbose
for something used so often, and create

Sometimes the increase in indentation is undesirable,
which is what the Swift inspired guard is for. It
resembles let else of Rust but with more parseable
grammar, I believe it to be an improvement.

guard .Some(let v) = optional else return

Guards require control flow to diverge and the unique
keyword makes this control flow stand out better.

Another special control flow is pattern iteration.

while match .Some(let v) = foo() {
    print(v)
}

This is not a commonly used control flow feature
so it's fine getting slightly more verbose syntax.
No ambiguity with the match keyword is present
thanks to actual match being a postfix expression,
so one could absolutely use a match expression in
a boolean while loop.

The last place patterns can be used is of course
match expressions.

let r = value match {
    .Some(let v) -> v
    .None -> "default"
}

Match expressions are a postfix operation allowing
them to compose in chains.

let r = foo
    .do_stuff()
    .to_some_enum() match {
        .CaseOne -> "one"
        .CaseTwo -> "two"
        .CaseOther(let v) -> v
    }
    .apply(print)

This is a significant improvement from the current
languages, to some extent inspired by the C++
pattern matching proposal.

Here are some possible patterns so far

value match {
    (1, 2) -> {}
    (let a, b) -> {}
    (let mut a, b) -> {}
    (let &a, b) -> {}
    (let mut &a, b) -> {}
    (let a, .EnumCase(let value)) -> {}
    .EnumCase(.OtherCase(let value)) -> {}
    .EnumCase(_) -> {}
    .EnumCase -> {}
    .EnumCase or .OtherCase -> {}
    let object: ObjectSubtype -> {}
    .EnumCase(let value) where value.is_foo() -> {}
    (_, 1) -> {}
    (_, _) -> {}
    _ where a == b -> {}
    _ -> {}
}

:: docs/pitch.txt
--[[pod_format="raw",created="2026-03-14 21:18:24",icon=userdata("u8",16,16,""),modified="2026-03-19 13:13:11",revision=195]]
Hello!

I have been working on a programming language for
a while now, and I decided to implement the first
prototype compiler on the Picotron, since I finally
completed the specification.

Picotron will remain a first class target for the
language, with type-safe wrappers for the API
already provided by the `picotron` module
in the core libraries.

Pico-8 will probably be supported in the future,
but it would require its own backend mainly
due to how it implements Lua numbers differently.
The language can scale to even 8 bit platforms,
but using code compiled with the full Lua backend
will practically guarantee undefined behavior on
integers, fixed numbers, and floats especially.

I call it the Strawberry Programming Language.

It is an advanced language, more feature packed than
the latest versions of C++, but it's a lot easier.
Here's a list of the major features, some
not applicable to the current Picotron prototype:

- Portable, even to limited backends
such as Lua or the JVM with no linear memory.
- Functions with overloadable argument labels.
- Argument and return type overloading.
- Closures.
- C family syntax, newlines are part of the grammar
so there are no semicolons (unless needed to place
multiple expressions on one line).
- Overloading of common operators.
- Custom operators (left associative with the highest
precedence only). Also prefix/postfix operators.
- Operator functions still have normal names, allowing
their use in method chains without parentheses.
- Custom type-level prefix/postfix operators,
operators that transform types, such as the
postfix sugar for `Optional<Int>` as `Int?`, or
the prefix sugar for `Pointer<T>` as `*T`.
- Self types.
- Everything is an object. As the previous point
implies, even pointers are just structs, there
are no primitive types. The usual primitives are
just implemented with intrinsic expressions `#expr()`.
This means that one can read the source or see
documentation comments of conventionally primitive
operations, or that the language can restrict some
extensions such as pointer arithmetic on platforms
with no linear memory (GPUs, Lua, JVM etc) entirely
in language with understandable errors. Also, Int is
generic! One can abstract over all sizes through
the use of Int<size> for instance, since it's a struct.
- Immutability by default.
- Initializers.
- Implicit conversions. This combines well with
const only functions, so safe conversions can be
allowed at runtime, but potentially out of range
conversions can require explicit conversion at runtime
and work implicitly at compile time with a compile
error on range issues (through const overloads).
- Fixed point as the default decimal type to avoid
precision errors. Most languages have floats work
intuitively by handwaving away the nonsense, however
compromise does not belong in Strawberry.
Floats don't uphold any sensible numeric properties
so their API is verbose and they can't be
abstracted generically as they can't implement
any of the common numeric categories.
Fixed point can interoperate with integers far better
and is also just way faster. For instance implicitly
converting an integer of smaller or equal range to
its fixed point counterpart is always correct
(not the other way around of course) allowing clean
syntax like simply comparing integers and fixed point
for equality with no explicit conversions needed.
- Unsafe API tracking like Rust and Swift.
- Structs with value and destructive move semantics.
- Projections (like references but more generic).
- Strict lifetimes and exclusivity enforcement.
- Algebraic enums (cases can contain tuples).
- Classes (as syntactic sugar on any smart pointers).
- Foreign Classes (Java or other runtime interop).
- Single inheritance for classes, final by default.
- Categories, think Rust traits but used to
model semantics rather than functionality, so closer
to Swift protocols.
- Everything is an expression.
- Tuples (with support for named elements).
- Pattern matching (match/guard-let/if-let etc).
- Method chains are what it's about.
- Loops (for-in-where/while/while-let/loop).
- Labeled break with a value.
- Block expressions, the last expression is returned.
- Early returns.
- Named, multiple return values (through tuples).
- Destructuring and multiple assignment.
- Type/Value generic parameters with argument labels.
- Variadic generics (not implemented yet).
- Extensions, adding methods to all or a subset of
constrained types.
- Guaranteed, eager compile time evaluation.
- Checked, monomorphised exceptions (throws just
panic, unless a catch is used, then a separate
instantiation of the chain is compiled with the
exception propagated, generally as a union).
- Optional and Result types, for near all error
handling. Exceptions only exist for rare cases like
allocation failure (hence the name, *exceptional*).
Exceptions just avoid the mess that Rust has,
duplicating all allocating code with panicking and
safe variants. The compiler does that for you.
- Const functions/types (restricted compile time).
- Transparent compile time allocation, you can
allocate a list, append some numbers, and it will be
precomputed at compile time. In const context you
can even upcast runtime values to constants, so
a function could precompute data in a dynamic list
and return a fixed size array.
- Annotations, declaration attached
values for compile time reflection.
- Objects, singleton types with inheritance, they
can implement categories and 
- Computed properties, which because the language
uses projections rather than references can be
bound transparently.
- Result builers for high level declarative DSLs.
Compile time evaluation with reflection is far more
structured than the token based macros of Rust/Swift.
- Simple modules and visibility modifiers. All sources
specify a module path header, and module declarations
are qualified by that path. This is similar to Java.
Dependency management works by simply providing
search paths for Strawberry to collect files in.
There is no packaging system planned, Strawberry is
not intended to be a fragmented ecosystem with
thousands of transitive dependencies for even the
standard library, it is small and portable.
- Clean lifetime dependence with minimal syntax.

Generally, the language combines the best ideas from
languages like Rust, Swift, Kotlin, Java, C++ etc,
while throwing out the ideas that did not work.
It is also syntactically refined and very clean,
but not excessively terse.

With all of its features, I believe Strawberry is
the most complete programming language, and I have
taken great care to ensure it remains extremely
portable despite that fact. While languages like
Rust or C++ are okay, there are things I wish to do
like target unusual platforms like Picotron or the
PS2, platforms which have no support from LLVM and
don't support features these languages assume
(Picotron is not a linear memory platform, the
PS2 floats are not standard, and so on).

Strawberry is similar to Rust in
many ways but the most important difference is that
it does not enforce the patterns you can use.
You are free to choose, or use all of them at once.
Value types are of course more challenging to use
as safety requires strict lifetimes, but classes do
exist so feel free to use those for an easier time.

There are currently some limitations due to the
very alpha state of the language.
I will later transition the language to be self hosted
so that backends can be implemented portably,
with the bootstrap compiler being ported to ISO C.
Strawberry will still support Picotron by virtue of
being able to cross compile, it just won't *bootstrap*
on Picotron since it's not reasonable to maintain
multiple compilers.

The current compiler is also extremely slow, this is
expected, the bootstrap compiler/interpreter is
not meant for use, and any optimizations will only be
implemented in the self hosted code.

This alpha implementation is MIT licensed.

Here is the obligatory picotron hello world:

```
module main

import picotron

@Entry
fun main() {
    print("Hello, world!")
}
```

And this is how you'd use the typical
game loop using a singleton object:

```
module main

import picotron

@Entry
object MyGame: Game {
    // You can omit these, they have default
    // empty implementations, but I show them
    // for completeness of the example.
    fun initialize() {}
    
    fun update() {}
    
    fun draw() {
        // Clear with the dark blue color.
        clear(color: .id(1))
    }
}
```

In the future I will add high level support for the
native GUI system, as well as a system with
an annotation based automatic argument parser
for writing command line utilities.

I hope you like it and make something
really cool with it. Questions, feedback and
constructive criticism is welcome :)

:: docs/primitives.txt
--[[pod_format="raw",created="2026-03-11 09:20:20",modified="2026-03-11 09:31:01",revision=2]]
On the interaction of types and control flow.

There is a requirement for certain control flow
to be aware of the type system, such as booleans,
optionals, iterators, futures and so on. I would like
to avoid special casing for core types like
in Rust or Swift, and the mess that is C++.

Unfortunately, this is to some extent unavoidable,
but there is an in-between. Rather than hardcoding
these "primitive" types they are marked with
some intrinsic categories. It's not that different
of course but the important part is that all inherent
categories and primitive constructs are explicitly
announced as such in the source code. It is important
that one can just read the definition of for example
the Copyable category as a learning process.

:: edit/main.lua
--[[pod_format="raw",created="2026-03-17 16:28:20",icon=userdata("u8",16,16,""),modified="2026-03-25 13:17:57",revision=1689]]
__STRC_LIB_MODE = true
include "strc.lua"

local text_cursor = unpod("b64:bHo0ACEAAAAuAAAA-wVweHUAQyAHCgQQISABJwEgAQcBMAQAAHAgAScBICEQ")

function configure_window(cur)
	window {
		tabbed = true,
		icon = unpod("b64:bHo0ABsAAAAZAAAA8ApweHUAQyAICAR3cAcAByAHUDcAByAHgHdw"),
		pauseable = false,
		autoclose = false,
		cursor = cur or 1
	}
end
configure_window()

function text_input()
	if (not peektext()) return nil
	return readtext()
end

function stri(s, str, i)
	local b = sub(s, 1, i - 1)
	local a = sub(s, i)
	return b .. str .. a
end

function delstri(s, i)
	local b = sub(s, 1, i - 1)
	local a = sub(s, i + 1)
	return b .. a
end

function cindent(s)
	local c = 0
	for char in all(s) do
		if char == " " then c += 1 else break end
	end
	return c
end

local config = {
	leading = 3,
	apple = true,
	banana_decls = true,
	blink_rate = 30,
	blink_delay = 30,
	column_guide = 80,
	autoclose_braces = true,
	show_spaces = false,
	diagnostic_delay = 30,
	free_scroll = false,
	scroll_speed = 4
}

function apply_config()
	menuitem {
		id ="show_spaces",
		label = config.show_spaces
			and "\^:007f4f4f4f7f0000 Show Spaces: On"
			or  "\^:007f7979797f0000 Show Spaces: Off",
		action = function()
			config.show_spaces = not config.show_spaces
			apply_config()
		end
	}
	menuitem {
		id ="banana_decls",
		label = config.banana_decls
			and "\^:007f4f4f4f7f0000 Banana Decls: On"
			or  "\^:007f7979797f0000 Banana Decls: Off",
		action = function()
			config.banana_decls = not config.banana_decls
			apply_config()
			clear_colorizer_cache()
		end
	}
end

-- The editor operates on split lines. This allows us to easily run
-- the Strawberry tokenizer and apply crude syntax highlighting.
-- Strawberry scopes keywords to very narrow context so naively
-- highlighting them will cause false positives.
local source
local lines
local colorizer_cache = {}
local changes = 0
local sel_ln = 1
local sel_col = 1
local sel_from_ln
local sel_from_col
local tick = 0
local blink = true
local scroll_x = 0
local scroll_y = 0
local scroll_vx = 0
local scroll_vy = 0

local server
local diagnostics = {}
local diagnostic_delay = 0
local sir
local lang_suggestions
local lang_hover

function resolve_lang_suggestions()

end

function resolve_lang_hover()

end

function apply_lang_suggestion()

end

function start_server()
	local processes = fetch("/ram/system/processes.pod")
	for process in all(processes) do
		if process.name == "strc" then
			server = process.id
			send_message(server, { event = "register_client", client_id = pid() })
		end
	end
	
	if not server then
		server = create_process("strc.lua", {
			argv = { "cserve", tostring(pid()) }
		})
	end
end
start_server()

function ask_server_for_diagnostics()
	send_message(server, { event = "get_diagnostics" }, function(msg)
		for diag in all(msg.diags) do
			if diag.span.first.source == pwf() then
				diagnostics[diag.span.first.line] = diag
			end
		end
		
		if (msg.sir) sir = msg.sir
	end)
end
ask_server_for_diagnostics()

function ask_server_to_run()
	send_message(server, { event = "try_run" })
end

local undo_stack = create_undo_stack(
	function()
		if (source == nil) return nil
		return {
			source = source,
			lines = lines,
			sel_ln = sel_ln,
			sel_col = sel_col,
			scroll_x = scroll_x,
			scroll_y = scroll_y
		}
	end,
	function(obj)
		if (obj == nil) return
		source = obj.source
		lines = obj.lines
		sel_ln = obj.sel_ln
		sel_col = obj.sel_col
		scroll_x = obj.scroll_x
		scroll_y = obj.scroll_y
		colorizer_cache = {}
		mutated()
	end
)

function clear_colorizer_cache()
	colorizer_cache = {}
end

function deselect()
	sel_from_ln, sel_from_col = nil, nil
end

function get_selection_bounds()
	if not sel_from_ln or not sel_from_col then
		return nil
	end

	local start_ln, start_col = sel_ln, sel_col
	local end_ln, end_col = sel_from_ln, sel_from_col

	-- normalize direction
	if start_ln > end_ln or (start_ln == end_ln and start_col > end_col) then
		start_ln, start_col, end_ln, end_col =
			end_ln, end_col, start_ln, start_col
	end

	return start_ln, start_col, end_ln, end_col
end

function get_sel_string()
	if not sel_from_ln or not sel_from_col then
		return nil
	end
	
	local start_ln, start_col = sel_ln, sel_col
	local end_ln, end_col = sel_from_ln, sel_from_col
	
	if start_ln > end_ln or (start_ln == end_ln and start_col > end_col) then
		start_ln, start_col, end_ln, end_col =
			end_ln, end_col, start_ln, start_col
	end
	
	if start_ln == end_ln then
		local ln = lines[start_ln] or ""
		return sub(ln, start_col, end_col - 1)
	end
	
	local result = {}
	
	local first = lines[start_ln] or ""
	add(result, sub(first, start_col))
	
	for ln = start_ln + 1, end_ln - 1 do
		add(result, lines[ln] or "")
	end
	
	local last = lines[end_ln] or ""
	add(result, sub(last, 1, end_col - 1))
	
	return table.concat(result, "\n")
end

-- Resets the blink cycle, used to stop blinking for a while
-- immediately after any motion. Cursors blink to help identify them,
-- but blinking during motion is distracting; not only do we
-- already know where the cursor is, we are moving it ourselves already which
-- inherently draws the eye to the cursor. Not so when it keeps blinking,
-- it might just disappear during it's motion which breaks spatial consistency.
function cursor_acted()
	tick = 0
	blink = true
end

function mutated()
	changes += 1
	diagnostics = {}
	diagnostic_delay = 0
	deselect()
end

function split_lines(str)
	local buf = {}
	
	for ln in str:gmatch("([^\n]*)\n?") do
		if ln == "" and #buf > 0 and buf[#buf] == "" then
			break
		end
		
		add(buf, ln)
	end
	
	return buf
end

function reflow()
	commit_source()
	lines = split_lines(source)
	colorizer_cache = {}
end

function init_source(obj)
	source = obj or ""
	-- Ensure the POSIX trailing newline.
	if (source[#source] ~= "\n") source = source .. "\n"
	lines = split_lines(source)
end

function commit_source()
	source = table.concat(lines, "\n")
end

-- Figures out the actual cursor position. The stored column is
-- generally preserved when traversing shorter lines so we need
-- to be able to figure out where the cursor is supposed to be.
function sel()
	return sel_ln, mid(1, sel_col, #(lines[sel_ln] or {}) + 1)
end

-- Some actions commit the actual position, discarding the preserved column.
function reify_sel()
	sel_ln, sel_col = sel()
end

function move_line_up()
	if sel_ln > 1 then
		undo_stack:checkpoint()
		reify_sel()
		add(lines, deli(lines, sel_ln), sel_ln - 1)
		sel_ln -= 1
		cursor_acted()
		mutated()
		clear_colorizer_cache()
	end
end

function move_line_down()
	if sel_ln <= #lines then
		undo_stack:checkpoint()
		if (sel_ln == #lines) add(lines, "")
		reify_sel()
		add(lines, deli(lines, sel_ln), sel_ln + 1)
		sel_ln += 1
		cursor_acted()
		mutated()
		clear_colorizer_cache()
	end
end

function cursor_up()
	if sel_ln > 1 then
		sel_ln -= 1
		cursor_acted()
	end
end

function cursor_down()
	if sel_ln <= #lines then
		sel_ln += 1
		cursor_acted()
	end
end

function cursor_left()
	reify_sel()
	if sel_col > 1 then
		sel_col -= 1
		cursor_acted()
	end
end

function cursor_right()
	reify_sel()
	if lines[sel_ln] and sel_col <= #lines[sel_ln] then
		sel_col += 1
		cursor_acted()
	end
end

function mouse_pos()
	local x, y = mouse()
	return mouse_to_pos(x, y)
end

function mouse_to_pos(x, y)
	y += scroll_y
	x += scroll_x
	x += 2 -- Adjust selection optically, we select by space-between not by glyph.
	
	if (x < 25) return
	
	local line_height = 8 + config.leading
	
	-- Find line.
	local ln = (y - 3) // line_height + 1
	ln = mid(1, ln, #lines + 1) -- ???
	
	-- Find column.
	local col = (x - 30) // 5 + 1
	col = mid(1, col, #(lines[ln] or {}) + 1)
	
	return ln, col
end

function cursor_click(x, y)
	reify_sel()
	
	if key("shift") then
		if not sel_from_ln and not sel_from_col then
			sel_from_ln, sel_from_col = sel_ln, sel_col
		end
	else
		deselect()
	end
	
	sel_ln, sel_col = mouse_to_pos(x, y)
	cursor_acted()
end

function cursor_drag(x, y)
	reify_sel()
	
	if not sel_from_ln and not sel_from_col then
		sel_from_ln, sel_from_col = sel_ln, sel_col
	end
	
	local x, y = mouse()
	sel_ln, sel_col = mouse_to_pos(x, y)
	
	cursor_acted()
end

function cursor_write(text)
	reify_sel()
	
	local compensate = 0
	if config.autoclose_braces then
		if text == "{" then
			text = text .. "}"
			compensate = -1
		end
	end
	
	local ln, col = sel()
	
	if (not lines[ln]) add(lines, "")
	lines[ln] = stri(lines[ln], text, col)
	colorizer_cache[ln] = nil
	
	sel_col += #text + compensate
	cursor_acted()
	mutated()
end

function cursor_delete()
	reify_sel()
	
	local ln, col = sel()
	
	colorizer_cache[ln] = nil
	colorizer_cache[ln - 1] = nil
	
	if lines[ln] and col > 1 then
		lines[ln] = delstri(lines[ln], col - 1)
		sel_col -= 1
	elseif lines[ln] and ln > 1 and col == 1 then
		local dest_col = #lines[ln - 1] + 1
		lines[ln - 1] = lines[ln - 1] .. lines[ln]
		deli(lines, ln)
		colorizer_cache = {}
		
		sel_ln = ln - 1
		sel_col = dest_col
	elseif not lines[ln] then
		sel_ln -= 1
		sel_col = #lines[ln - 1] + 1
	end
	
	cursor_acted()
	mutated()
end

function cursor_delete_to_start()
	reify_sel()
	
	if sel_col ~= 1 then
		while sel_col ~= 1 do cursor_delete() end
	else
		cursor_delete()
	end
	
	mutated()
end

function cursor_newline()
	reify_sel()
	
	local ln, col = sel()
	
	local autoscope = false
	local inferred_indent = cindent(lines[ln])
	if
		lines[ln] and
		config.autoclose_braces and
		lines[ln][col - 1] == "{" and
		lines[ln][col] == "}"
	then
		autoscope = true
	end
	
	if not lines[ln] then
		add(lines, "")
	else
		local old = lines[ln]
		lines[ln] = sub(old, 1, col - 1)
		if autoscope then
			add(lines, string.rep(" ", inferred_indent) .. sub(old, col, -1), ln + 1)
		else
			add(lines, sub(old, col, -1), ln + 1)
		end
	end
	sel_ln += 1
	sel_col = 1
	
	if autoscope then
		add(lines, string.rep(" ", inferred_indent + 4), sel_ln)
		sel_col += inferred_indent + 4
	end
	
	colorizer_cache = {}
	cursor_acted()
	mutated()
end

function scroll(x, y)
	if not key("ctrl") then
		scroll_y = max(0, scroll_y - y * config.scroll_speed)
		if (config.free_scroll) scroll_x = mid(0, scroll_x + x * config.scroll_speed, 340)
	else
		scroll_x = mid(0, scroll_x - y * config.scroll_speed, 340)
	end
end

on_event("click", function(e)
	cursor_click(e.mx, e.my, true)
end)

on_event("drag", function(e)
	cursor_drag(e.mx, e.my)
end)

on_event("hover", function(e)
	if e.mx > 25 and e.my < 250 then
		configure_window(text_cursor)
	else
		configure_window()
	end
end)

on_event("mousewheel", function(e)
	scroll(e.wheel_x, e.wheel_y)
end)

wrangle_working_file {
	save_state = function()
		commit_source()
		return source
	end,
	load_state = function(obj, meta)
		init_source(obj)
	end,
	state_hint = function()
		return changes
	end,
	untitled_filename = "/ram/cart/src/main.str"
}
apply_config()

on_event("modified:" .. pwf(),
	function(msg)
		ask_server_for_diagnostics()
	end
)

function strawberry_pal()
	fetch("/system/fonts/lil_mono.font"):poke(0x4000)
	
	-- The one, the only, the legendary Strawberry color palette
	-- which has highlighted my editors for many years now.
	pal(33, 0x101010, 2) -- very black
	pal(34, 0x151515, 2) -- black
	pal(35, 0x1a1a1a, 2) -- dark
	pal(36, 0x333333, 2) -- gray
	pal(37, 0x808080, 2) -- light
	pal(38, 0xe1e1e1, 2) -- white
	
	pal(39, 0xf1896b, 2) -- orange     :: string
	pal(40, 0xf8c950, 2) -- lemon      :: number
	pal(41, 0x75accc, 2) -- blueberry  :: method
	pal(42, 0xa6dd98, 2) -- lime       :: struct
	pal(43, 0xc8dd86, 2) -- apple      :: class
	pal(44, 0xedbf7a, 2) -- banana     :: declaration
	pal(45, 0xe75575, 2) -- strawberry :: keyword
	
	pal(46, 0x0d0d0d, 2) -- shadow
	pal(47, 0xc1c1c1, 2) -- subtle
	pal(48, 0x6f868f, 2) -- comment
	pal(49, 0x131313, 2) -- column guide
	pal(50, 0x2f2f2f, 2) -- whitespace hints
	pal(51, 0x2d1c20, 2) -- error
	pal(52, 0x576137, 2) -- selection
	pal(53, 0x24201a, 2) -- warning
	pal(54, 0x122632, 2) -- info
end

local keywords = {}
for keyword in all({
	"guard", "get", "set", "Nil", "nil", "lazy", "object", "is", "annotation",
	"Any", "inherent", "unsafe", "base", "as", "extern", "foreign", "open", "async",
	"await", "gen", "inline", "use", "import", "true", "false", "else", "module",
	"then", "throw", "throws", "catch", "try", "do", "and", "or", "not", "if",
	"let", "mut", "subscript", "extend", "Self", "Type", "self", "repeat", "type",
	"implicit", "init", "deinit", "where", "fun", "pub", "enum", "category", "class",
	"struct", "operator", "infix", "prefix", "postfix", "match", "break", "loop",
	"while", "for", "in", "const", "static", "return", "when", "new"
}) do keywords[keyword] = true end

local decl_keywords = {}
for keyword in all({
	"object", "annotation", "type", "enum", "category", "class", "struct"
}) do decl_keywords[keyword] = true end

local next_is_intrinsic = false
local previous_token = nil
function colorize(tok)
	if tok.sym == "str" then
		return 39
	elseif tok.sym == "number" then
		return 40
	elseif tok.sym == "ident" and tok.symbolic then
		return 38
	elseif tok.sym == "ident" and next_is_intrinsic then
		next_is_intrinsic = false
		return 41
	elseif tok.sym == "ident" and keywords[tok.buf] then
		return 45
	elseif tok.sym == "ident" and tok.buf[1] >= "A" and tok.buf[1] <= "Z" then
		if previous_token and decl_keywords[previous_token.buf] and
			config.banana_decls
		then
			return 44
		else
			if config.apple then
				return 43
			else
				return 42
			end
		end
	elseif tok.sym == "ident" then
		return 47
	elseif tok.sym == "#" then
		next_is_intrinsic = true
		return 38
	else
		return 38
	end
end

-- A function which analyzes the SIR in search of the hovered construct
-- and provides the declaration string as well as documentation if present.
-- This coroutine based function drives the core experience of all
-- code intelligence functionality across the editor.
function assist_lookup_hovered_construct()
	
end

-- A function which heuristically analyzes a partial expression, invoked
-- by typing `.` or using the completion shortcut. It then attemtps to seach
-- the last obtained non-erroneous SIR for possible candidates.
function assist_lookup_code_completion()
	
end

function _update()
	tick += 1
	
	if tick % config.blink_rate == 0 and tick > config.blink_delay then
		blink = not blink
	end
	
	if key("ctrl") and keyp("enter") then
		ask_server_to_run()
	elseif key("ctrl") and key("shift") and keyp("z")
		or key("ctrl") and keyp("y")
	then
		undo_stack:redo()
	elseif key("ctrl") and keyp("z") then
		undo_stack:undo()
	elseif key("ctrl") and keyp("c") then
		set_clipboard(get_sel_string())
	elseif key("ctrl") and keyp("v") then
		undo_stack:checkpoint()
		cursor_write(get_clipboard())
		reflow()
	elseif key("ctrl") and keyp("backspace") then
		undo_stack:checkpoint()
		cursor_delete_to_start()
	else
		if key("alt") and keyp("up") then
			move_line_up()
		elseif keyp("up") then
			cursor_up()
		end
		
		if key("alt") and keyp("down") then
			move_line_down()
		elseif keyp("down") then
			cursor_down()
		end
		
		if (keyp("left")) cursor_left()
		if (keyp("right")) cursor_right()
		
		for text in text_input do
			undo_stack:checkpoint()
			cursor_write(text)
		end
		if keyp("backspace") then
			undo_stack:checkpoint()
			 cursor_delete()
		end
		if keyp("enter") then
			undo_stack:checkpoint()
			cursor_newline()
		end
		if keyp("tab") then
			undo_stack:checkpoint()
			cursor_write("    ")
		end
	end
	
	-- Esoteric, but Lua can't answer the count of sets and dictionaries.
	for _ in pairs(diagnostics) do
		diagnostic_delay += 1
		break
	end
end

function _draw()
	strawberry_pal()
	redraw() -- todo: don't do this if nothing changed.
end

function redraw()
	cls(34)
	
	camera(scroll_x, 0)
	rrectfill(0, 0, 24, 270, 0, 33)
	line(24, 0, 24, 269, 35)
	line(23, 0, 23, 269, 46)
	camera()
	
	-- The top bar.
	do
		rrectfill(25, 0, 480, 11, 0, 34)
		--line(0, 11, 479, 11, 36)
		--line(25, 12, 479, 12, 46)
		line(0, 0, 479, 0, 35)
		pset(25, 1, 35)
		pset(23, 1, 35)
	end
	
	camera(scroll_x, 0)
	
	if config.column_guide then
		draw_column_guide(config.column_guide)
	end
	
	camera(scroll_x, scroll_y)
	
	local lines_drawn = 0
	for i = 1 + scroll_y // (8 + config.leading), #lines + 1 do
		local ypos = 3 + (i - 1) * (8 + config.leading)
		local ln = lines[i]
		
		if i == sel_ln then
			rrectfill(0, ypos, 23, 10, 0, 34)
			rrectfill(25, ypos - 1, 480, 10, 0, 35)
			if config.column_guide then
				local ln, col = sel()
				local posx = 29 + config.column_guide * 5
				fillp(0b1010010110100101)
				rrectfill(posx, ypos - 1, 480, 10, 0, 35 + (34 << 8))
				fillp()
			end
		end
		
		if diagnostics[i] and diagnostic_delay > config.diagnostic_delay then
			local diagnostic = diagnostics[i]
			
			local c = 51
			if diagnostic.kind == "error" then
				c = 51
			elseif diagnostic.kind == "warning" then
				c = 53
			elseif diagnostic.kind == "info" then
				c = 54
			end
			
			fillp(0b1010010110100101)
			rrectfill(0, ypos, 23, 10, 0, c + (33 << 8))
			fillp()
			rrectfill(25, ypos - 1, 480, 10, 0, c)
			if config.column_guide then
				fillp(0b1010010110100101)
				local ln, col = sel()
				local posx = 29 + config.column_guide * 5
				rrectfill(posx, ypos - 1, 480, 10, 0, c + (34 << 8))
				fillp()
			end
		end
		
		local fmt = tostring(i)
		fmt = string.rep(" ", 4 - #fmt) .. fmt
		print("\014" .. fmt, 4, ypos + 2, i == sel_ln and 37 or 36)
		
		if (i == #lines + 1) break
		
		next_is_intrinsic = false
		previous_token = nil
		local colorizer = colorizer_cache[i]
		if not colorizer then
			colorizer = {}
			pcall(function()
				for token in tokenize(ln) do
					local col = colorize(token)
					previous_token = token
					for ci = token.column - token.count + 1, token.column do
						colorizer[ci] = col
					end
				end
			end)
			colorizer_cache[i] = colorizer
		end
		
		if sel_from_ln then
			for ci = 0, max(#ln, 1) - 1 do
				local start_ln, start_col = sel_ln, sel_col
				local end_ln, end_col = sel_from_ln, sel_from_col
				
				if start_ln > end_ln or (start_ln == end_ln and start_col > end_col) then
					start_ln, start_col, end_ln, end_col = end_ln, end_col, start_ln, start_col
				end
				
				local inside = false
				if i > start_ln and i < end_ln then
					inside = true
				elseif i == start_ln and i == end_ln then
					inside = ci + 1 >= start_col and ci + 1 < end_col
				elseif i == start_ln then
					inside = ci + 1 >= start_col
				elseif i == end_ln then
					inside = ci + 1 < end_col
				end
				
				if inside then
					local x = 28 + ci * 5
					local y = ypos - 1
					local w = #ln == 0 and 4 or 8
					local h = 10
					rrectfill(x, y, w, h, 1, 52)
				end
			end
		end
		
		cursor(30, ypos)
		local is_comment = false
		for ci, char in ipairs(ln) do
			if (char == "/" and ln[ci + 1] == "/") is_comment = true
			if is_comment then
				color(48)
			else
				color(colorizer[ci] or 38)
			end
			
			if config.show_spaces and char == " " then
				color(50)
				print("_\0")
			else
				print(char .. "\0")
			end
		end
		
		if diagnostics[i] and diagnostic_delay > config.diagnostic_delay then
			local diagnostic = diagnostics[i]
			
			local c = 45
			if diagnostic.kind == "error" then
				c = 45
			elseif diagnostic.kind == "warning" then
				c = 44
			elseif diagnostic.kind == "info" then
				c = 41
			end
			
			color(c)
			print("  " .. diagnostics[i].reason .. "\0")
		end
		
		lines_drawn += 1
		if (lines_drawn == 23) break
	end
	
	if blink then
		local ln, col = sel()
		
		local csx = 29 + (col - 1) * 5
		local csy = 3 + (ln - 1) * 11
		local csh = 7
		line(csx, csy, csx, csy + csh, 7)
		pset(csx - 1, csy - 1) pset(csx + 1, csy - 1)
		pset(csx - 1, csy + csh + 1) pset(csx + 1, csy + csh + 1)
	end
	
	-- Overlay pass.
	local lines_drawn = 0
	for i = 1 + scroll_y // (8 + config.leading), #lines + 1 do
		local ypos = 3 + (i - 1) * (8 + config.leading)
		local ln = lines[i]
		
		if diagnostics[i] and diagnostic_delay > config.diagnostic_delay then			
			local mln, mcol = mouse_pos()
			local help_text = diagnostics[i].help_text
			if i == mln and help_text then
				draw_dialogue_box(27, ypos + 11, help_text)
			end
		end
		
		lines_drawn += 1
		if (lines_drawn == 23) break
	end
	
	camera()
	
	-- The bottom bar.
	do
		local ln, col = sel()
		rrectfill(0, 248, 480, 11, 0, 0)
		print(
			string.format("\014line %d:%d of %d", ln, col, #lines + 1),
			3, 251, 36
		)
	end
end

function draw_column_guide(limit)
	local ln, col = sel()
	local posx = 29 + limit * 5
	rrectfill(posx, 1, 480, 270, 0, 49)
end

function draw_modal_shadow()
	poke(0x550b, 0x3f)
	fillp(0b0101101001011010)
	rectfill(0, 0, 479, 269, 33)
	fillp()
	poke(0x550b, 0x00)
end

function draw_modal_code_outline()
	
end

function draw_dialogue_box(x, y, text)
	local lines = split(text, "\n")
	
	local text_width = 16
	for ln in all(lines) do
		text_width = max(text_width, #ln * 5)
	end
	
	local w = text_width + 7
	local h = #lines * 11 + 5
	
	rrectfill(x, y, w, h, 1, 35)
	rrect(x, y, w, h, 1, 36)
	rrect(x - 1, y - 1, w + 2, h + 2, 2, 46)
	
	print(text, x + 4, y + 4, 37)
end

