:: readme.txt
--[[pod_format="raw",created="2026-03-10 08:07:09",icon=userdata("u8",16,16,""),modified="2026-06-05 18:22:22",revision=189]]Welcome to the Strawberry Programming Language!
--[[pod_type="gfx"]]unpod("b64:bHo0AIcBAAB_AgAA8iVweHUAQyCAEAQQMQARADHwYwE-GwEOAwEOIwEQ8SnwJgEOEQ5jEQMBAAEmAQYBBgEmQScBAgAzBwEHCgACDACw8CcRA3gDERARBhEpAIsGYQcxBxEHAQIANiEHAQIA8gzwKAEIHw4YDxgIDRgBIBEGESYBFlEnEQcRFxFUACIXEQIA9QAnAfAnAQgPDg8XHw4NWAFkADaBBxFkABonYgAhIQc1AGUsKA0YDQgzADkmQSczAAS_AAIOAIHwJwEYDEgtCPwAMCcBCDsAAgIA9QcBEPFB8A8BaD0IARABJgEmERYRFgEmAgBhFiEWQQYhCAACJwEBHgBA8BABGEMAaB0IASABBgIAEyEIAAA9AATNAD5hBiEgAMAGIQYh8BEBKD0IATBoAAIrADIhFhGPATcGAQY-ABcmPQARJiYAo-ARAQgNCC0YATAXAA8CAAQERQA-AQZBKAAIYCHwEgEIHQ4BE0BPAAeIABYB0wABBgAnQSYSABUmCADQ8BMBOAFQ8UHwFDHwZg==")

This is a small getting started guide explaining
the capabilities of the language and how to use
the strc frontend for Picotron.

-- Installation --------------------------------------
To use the compiler, strc, it needs to be installed
along with the core libraries. The provided script
named "install.lua" will do the following things:
- Copy strc.lua to /appdata/system/util/strc.lua
- Copy srt.lua to /appdata/shared/strawberry/srt.lua
- Copy std to /appdata/shared/strawberry/std
- Copy templates to /appdata/shared/strawberry/templates

Simply load the cartridge and run `install`.

-- Getting started ----------------------------------
By default Strawberry will look for modules in the
following places, recursively:
- /ram/cart/src (your program goes here)
- /ram/cart/lib (your dependencies go here)
- /appdata/shared/strawberry/std (the core libraries)
- /appdata/shared/strawberry/lib (global libraries)

To initialize a Strawberry project in the loaded
cart, run `strc init` or `strc init -t <template>`.
Templates are picked from the template folder by
name, and the following options are provided
out of the box:
- hello (default), a main function entry point.
- game, a main object with initialize/update/draw.

To build the loaded project use `strc build` and to
build and run use `strc run`.

The program will default to writing
over /ram/cart/main.lua and will include the runtime,
srt.lua, embedded in the file already.

Being a compiled language, Strawberry files
do not need to be distributed with the cart.
In the spirit of Picotron however, I would recommend
keeping them in exports for others to see unless
the cart is too big to be exported. In such a case
I would recommend still providing the source code
but in a separate archive instead.

-- Source structure ---------------------------------
Strawberry sees the world in modules. Any source file
has to have a module header with a path:

```
module main
module picotron
module picotron.io
```

The file structure is irrelevant, only that they
exist. To support that, the compiler uses
module paths, a list of directories to search for
module source files.

Additional paths can be specified with -M <path>
or with -Mr <path> to make the path recursive.

Module names are best made simple and descriptive,
and ideally just one word.

The module header can declare the source unit
as being ignored, this aborts even parsing the file.
It can be used for work-in-progress files that
would prevent compilation.

```
ignored module main
```

-- Functions ----------------------------------------

-- Value semantics ----------------------------------
Strawberry is a language primarily focused on values,
so most types behave like numbers in most languages,
always implicitly copied everywhere.

While in Lua this would not be efficient like it is
natively, most of the language is designed around
immutable bindings which is the default. The only
things you'd usually want to mutate in place are
non-copyable types like collections which are just
moved around.
So, the Lua backend for Strawberry applies a
variant of copy-on-write for all values, where only
binding a copyable type as mutable performs the copy.

-- Move semantics -----------------------------------
Some types can't be copied freely, either due to
performance cost (like large collections)

-- Reference semantics ------------------------------
Strawberry supports classes, where a base class is
required and provides the fundamental representation
for all derived classes in the form of a container.

Effectively, custom class runtimes, which is probably
less useful in the context of Picotron than it is
when targeting more difficult backends.

The pico library provides an Object base class which
implements class behavior in terms of Lua metatables
and its garbage collector for you.
Note that it will crash on shared mutable access
in order to maintain safety.

With classes it is possible to structure code
in a very traditional object oriented hierarchy
for anyone who likes that style of coding, but
do not feel forced to use classes, the language
is great with any number of feature combinations.

-- Projections --------------------------------------

:: spec.txt
--[[pod_format="raw",created="2026-06-05 18:22:09",icon=userdata("u8",16,16,""),modified="2026-06-09 15:18:48",revision=154]]
